## Architecture Notes

### Agent-First Routing Key (Preserved from v1.0.0)

The strategy uses agent name as the primary routing key, not generic task type. This is intentional: different agents performing the same abstract task (e.g., "code review") have different quality requirements and context sizes.

```
agent name → model tier → specific model (with fallback chain)
```

### 4-Tier Hierarchy (Preserved from v1.0.0)

| Tier | Model(s) | Use Case | Cost |
|------|----------|---------|------|
| Tier 0 | Claude Opus | Critical decisions, architecture, final escalation | Highest |
| Tier 1 | Claude Sonnet / Haiku | Complex reasoning, synthesis, API-fallback | Medium |
| Tier 2 | Ollama Large (Qwen2.5-32B-Coder, etc.) | Code generation, refactoring, test generation | Low |
| Tier 3 | Ollama Small (Qwen2.5-7B-Coder, etc.) | File reading, simple edits, repair loops | Lowest |

### PipelineModelRouter Integration (APIP-0040)

The `PipelineModelRouter` at `packages/backend/orchestrator/src/pipeline/model-router.ts` reads from the `wint.model_assignments` table (lego_dev, port 5432) with a 30s in-memory cache. DB-backed overrides take precedence over static YAML config. Cache invalidation is single-process only in Phase 0.

**Critical**: Model identifier strings in `WINT-0220-STRATEGY.yaml` must match exactly the string conventions used by `PipelineModelRouter`'s `agent_pattern` format. Mismatched identifiers cause silent cold-start fallback behavior without error messages (APIP-3050 lesson).

### Affinity Routing (APIP-3040/3050/3060 — New Since v1.0.0)

The pipeline now supports learning-aware routing where the `PipelineModelRouter` can use learned model affinities to prefer specific models for specific agents based on historical quality data. The strategy document should document this as an additional routing layer above the static tier assignments.

